SIMPLE: intimation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intimation
<hw>In`ti*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intimatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>intimation</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of intimating; also, the thing
intimated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Announcement; declaration.</def>
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They made an edict with an <qex>intimation</qex> that whosoever
killed a stork, should be banished.</q> <rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A hint; an obscure or indirect suggestion or notice;
a remote or ambiguous reference; <as>as, he had given only
<ex>intimations</ex> of his design</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Without mentioning the king of England, or giving the least
<qex>intimation</qex> that he was sent by him.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intime</ent>⟦br⟧
